  "summary": "After discovering a woman's body in a fur coat inside a stone sarcophagus in the warehouse, Lucy drives to a post office to call Miss Marple. Lucy informs Miss Marple of the discovery in the antique-filled warehouse and suggests calling the police, to which Miss Marple advises her to tell the truth to the authorities. Lucy then calls the police station to report the body found at Rutherford Hall.\n\nUpon returning to Rutherford Manor, Lucy seeks out Emma to inform her of the discovery privately, hoping to avoid upsetting Emma's sick father, Mr. Crickenshaw. Emma is stunned and expresses frustration that Lucy did not inform her before contacting the police. Lucy explains she used the post office phone to avoid being overheard by a boy.\n\nThe police arrive, led by Bacon. As Emma has called Dr. Camper to attend to her father, she is escorted out of the warehouse. Dr. Camper, an affable and cynical physician, observes Emma and comments on her instinct to care for the men in her family. Bacon informs the doctor that the coroner, Johnstone, estimates the woman was killed two to three weeks ago. Despite the unpleasant smell, Dr. Camper expresses curiosity about the victim's identity. Mr. Crickenshaw, who purchased the stone coffin in Florence years prior, joins the group and insists on fulfilling his duty to see the body despite the repulsive scene.",
